Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

The dataset has 21 columns and 10,000 records. The columns are:

  • id, imdb_id, popularity, budget, revenue, original_title, cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, runtime, genres, production_companies, release_date, vote_count, vote_average, release_year, budget_adj, and revenue_adj.

Tip: In this section of the report, provide a brief introduction to the dataset you've selected/downloaded for analysis. Read through the description available on the homepage-links present here. List all column names in each table, and their significance. In case of multiple tables, describe the relationship between tables.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. What are the top 10 movies with the highest runtime?
  2. What are the top 10 movies with the highest revenue? Compare with the revenue_adj.
  3. What are the top 10 movies with the highest budget? Compare with the budget_adj.
  4. What are the most popular movies based on popularity score?
  5. In what year was the highest total revenue generated?
  6. What is the total number of movies produced each year?
  7. Which year has the highest total budget?
  8. Do movies with long runtime cost more money to make? Is there a correlation between runtime and budget?
  9. Do movies with long runtime have higher revenue? Is there a correlation between runtime and revenue?
  10. Do movies with a high budget generate high revenue? Is there a correlation between budget and revenue?
  11. Is there a correlation between revenue and revenue_adj?

  12. Is there a correlation between budget and budget_adj?

  13. Is there a relationship between vote count and vote average

  14. Are movies with high vote counts more popular? (compare vote count and popularity score)

  15. Do popular movies generate more revenue?

  16. Which Movie Genre has the highest number of movies?

  17. Which movie genre generated the highest average revenue? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)
  18. Which movie genre has the highest average budget? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)
  19. Which movie genre has the highest average vote count? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)
  20. Which movie genre has the highest average vote average? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)
  21. Which movie genre has the highest average runtime? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)
  22. Which movie genre has the highest average popularity score? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)

The next step is to get rid of these columns.

There is one duplicate value. This can skew the result of our analysis. If we wanted to get a sum of all the budgets, the budget of the duplicate row will be included in our result. This which will give us the wrong result. In the data cleaning stage, the duplicate value will be removed.

Data Cleaning¶

Some columns that won't be necessary for our analysis will be dropped.

The id column contains unique values for each movie. The cardinality is high. The same applies to the imdb_id column. These columns will be dropped.

The homepage contain links to the movie. It won't be useful for analysis. It will be dropped. The release_date column won't be needed for this analysis. It will be removed. The release_year will be used instead.

The overview column consist of the movie description. It won't be needed for analyis. The keywords column will also be dropped.

The following columns will also be dropped because they contain missing values cast, director, tagline, genres, production_companies.

Question 17: Which movie genre generated the highest average revenue? (Compare Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)¶

In [180]:
def compare_genre(column_name, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """"Fuction to compare the some movie genres with a numeric column
    
    column_name: str, attribute: which is the column name,
    title: str, title of the plot,
    xlabel: str, label of the x axis,
    ylabel: str, label of the y axis.    
    """
    
    # use the getattr function to treat the column_name parameter
    # as an attribute of the df_genre dataframe
    
    adv = getattr(df_genre.query('adventure==True'), column_name).mean()
    action = getattr(df_genre.query('action==True'), column_name).mean()
    thriller = getattr(df_genre.query('thriller==True'), column_name).mean()
    sci = getattr(df_genre.query('sci_fi==True'), column_name).mean()
    drama = getattr(df_genre.query('drama==True'), column_name).mean()

    xlist = [adv, action, thriller, sci, drama]
    label = ["Adventure", "Action", "Thriller", "Sci_Fi", "Drama"]

    # plot bar chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    plt.bar(np.arange(0,5), xlist)
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0,5), label, rotation=90)
    plt.title(title, size=14)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);

Conclusions¶

Data Cleaning

  1. There are missing data in the following columns: imdb_id, cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, genres, production_companies.

  2. I removed the columns. There was also a duplicate row. I removed the duplicate row.

  3. There were 10866 records and 21 columns in the dataset. After cleaning, there were 10865 records and 10 columns.

  2. From 1961 to 2015, the highest number of movies were released in 2014 (700 movies).

  3. Compared to other year, a lot of money was budgetted for movies in the year 2010 ($9,355,001,006).

  4. To analyze the runtime, budget and revenue columns, I created a subset of the original dataset without any 0 value in the revenue and budget columns. After removing the 0 values, there were 3854 records.

  5. The correlation between the budget and runtime variables is 0.26. There is a weak relationship between those variables.

  6. The correlation between the revenue and runtime variables is 0.25. There is also a weak relationship between those variables.

  7. The correlation between the revenue and budget variables is 0.69. There is a positive relationship between those variables. Further investigation is needed.

  8. There is a strong positive correlation between the revenue and revenue_adj. The correlation coefficient is 0.90.

  9. There is a strong positive correlation between the budget and budget_adj. The correlation coefficient is 0.96.

  10. There is a weak relationship between vote_count and vote_average. The correlation coefficient is 0.25.

  12. There is a positive correlation between the popularity of a movie and the revenue it generates. The correlation coefficient is 0.62. Remember, we are working with a subset of the original dataset (df_copy) with only 3854 records.

  13. Between the years 1961 and 2015, the drama and comedy movie genres have the highest number of movies released. This comparison is limited to 14 genres which include Thriller, Action, Adventure, Sci-Fi, Animation, Comedy, Crime, Documentary, Drama, Fantasy, Horror, Music, Mystery, Romance.

  14. Out of the following movie genres (Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Sci-Fi)

    • Adventure genre has generated the highest average revenue.
    • Adventure, Action and Sci-Fi genres have the highest average budget.
    • Adventure and Sci-Fi genres have the highest average vote count.
    • Drama and Adventure genres have the highest average vote average.
    • Drama and Adventure genres have the highest average runtime.

Limitations

  1. 5696 movies in the dataset have 0 budget. 6016 movies in the dataset have 0 revenue. 31 movies have a runtime of 0. It is one of the limitations in the project. Movies do not have 0 runtime or 0 revenue. Although there are cases where a movies can have low-budget. To improve the result of the analysis, the 0 values need to be updated to the actual movie budget, and revenue.

  2. This dataset is limited to movies from 1961 to 2015. For better results, the dataset should be updated to include movies from 2016 to 2022.

  3. The analysis of the movie genres is limited to Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, and Sci-Fi.
